shared_text:
Olney High School Band
August 9 at 10:30 PM Â·

Hey POOHS!

Mrs. Bennett and I found out yesterday about the passing of one of our dearest band director friends, John Tunnell. Some of you may remember him as part of the Divan of the Maskat Shrine which hosts the annual Oil Bowl game. He was a HUGE supporter of the Oil Bowl Band and a former director of the group, as well as a band director for many years in north Texas.

A "Celebration of Life" service is tomorrow (Monday) at 5:00 p.m. in Wichita Falls. This will make it very difficult to have rehearsal tomorrow evening, so we will not meet at all tomorrow.

Regular rehearsal will begin again on Tuesday, August 11 from 4-9:00 p.m.

Please also note that there will be no band uniform organizing session tomorrow afternoon, nor uniform checkout on Tuesday at 2:00 for Seniors and Juniors. Checkout has been suspended until we receive the uniforms back from the cleaners.

Please spread the word about tomorrow's cancellation of rehearsal - section leaders might want to check with your sections.

Thank you for your understanding as we honor our friend and mentor.

Mr. and Mrs. Bennett

Olney FFA
August 4 at 11:10 AM Â·

Our students have a few opportunities to participate virtually in some contests held by the state fair of Texas.

Students can practice their job interview skills by competing in the job interview contest. This is open to students in grades 9-12.

Your students can also participate in a public speaking contest as well as a science fair contest. Both of these are open to grades 3-12.

These are great opportunities to build valuable life skills and we are happy to assist your child with any of these contests. If you are interested in learning more email hharalson@olneyisd.net.

shared_text:
Olney Community Library and Arts Center
May 27 at 11:04 AM Â·

Calling all Junior High and High School students...Olney Community Library will be hosting a Summer Reading program for you as well! Top prize is worth just under $200!

Here's how it works...

Choose your own books - from the library (preferably), from home, from your grandma, from your friends!

Come to the library and mark on your Summer Reading sheet how many pages you read.

Keep reading!

The person who reads the MOST pages between May 15 and July 30 will win! YES, books you've read since school has been "officially" out count! You're welcome!! ;-)

It's so simple!! However, you MUST fill out the paperwork at the Library in order for your pages to count.

Proud to be a CUB at Olney Community Library!!

The Olney Police Department is partnered with Crime Stoppers in Wichita Falls and would like for you to learn about this safe and confidential way to report crime.

Signs will be posted around town with the phone number (940) 322-9888 to call.

You can also send Crime Stoppers a tip online:
https://www.wfcrime.com/

Or you can download the app P3 Intel from your app store with the same ease and confidentiality.

Paula Silva Acunaâ€Adopt a 2020 Senior from Olney Tx
April 16 at 1:44 PM Â·

This is Ricardo Pacheco Olney High School Senior 2020.
Ricardo is the son of Jose and Irene Pacheco. Ricardo will be the first student in the history of OHS to complete the 4 year computer science program. Ricardo is also a member of the first group to begin the OHS UIL BEST Robotics program, serving as a group leader for 3 years, and advancing the the State competition 2 years in a row. Ricardo and the team had the opportunity to work alongside personnel at Tower Fab to learn more about computer automated design and the mechanics of robotic manufacturing. He also competed 2 years in the GAMA Aviation design program, working closely with personnel at Air Tractor to learn about flight mechanics. Ricardo is also among the first to compete in the OHS UIL Computer Science competition for 4 years. In addition to his school extracurriculars, he was able to obtain a welding certificate, receive honors for his Ag Mechanics project at the state level, and works part time welding after school. Ricardo plans to attend TSTC in Sweetwater to study Electromechanical Technology.

Mary Jane Simmentalâ€Adopt a 2020 Senior from Olney Tx
April 15 at 10:15 PM Â·

Annie Reinke is a senior at Olney High School. She is a member of NHS, FFA, and Archer County 4H. She participates in UIL Jounalism. Annie enjoys raising cattle and lamb projects. In the fall, Annie will be joining the junior college Livestock judging team at Blinn College in Brenham, Texas. She will be leaving behind her heifers & calves to start pursuing an Agriculture Communications degree. Annie aspires to become an Aggie and complete her education at Texas A&M. She would someday like to work with a cattle breed association or the AKC in marketing and promotions. Annie has always had a passion for animals and journalism. The virus situation has limited Annie being able to compete at The Houston Livestock Show, Rodeo Austin, The Simmental Regional Show, and various jackpots that have been canceled as well. **Adopted** by Kristy Nantz, Judy Hammond, Bree DeVries, Julie Lane

Callie Gray is the daughter of Kevin and Sonja Gray. Callie has been in band since 6th grade and has played alto and bari sax. She has played golf all 4 years of high school, advancing to regionals in 10th and 11th grade and state in 10th grade. Callie was selected to play in the FCA All Star Golf Tournament this summer. She has been involved with children and teen programs with her church her entire life. Callie participated in the work program through school this year and is employed by Grace Care Center. She is currently working on her CNA license and plans to attend Vernon College in the fall to start her EMT classes and paramedic after that. Callie was able to travel to Portugal with her mom this past October for her senior trip. She enjoys hunting and fishing with her dad. Callie loves Cheetos, Reeses Cups, anything Cookies and Cream, Dr Pepper and all kinds of coffee drinks.

Olney High School Yearbook/Journalism Program
April 6 at 12:07 PM Â·

We still need photos! The Olney High School yearbook staff wants to put out as complete a yearbook as possible, even with the complications presented by Covid 19. To make that happen, we are going to need some help compiling photos of different events. At this time, we are asking the public for the following photos:

1) Softball action shots
2) Baseball action shots
3) OHS track action photos
4) OJH track action photos
5) Homeschool photos or "selfies" (Olney ISD students of all ages)

Email photos you wouldn't mind seeing in the yearbook to mkimbro@olneyisd.net.

Senior parents, we are also still accepting senior ads! Email mkimbro@olneyisd.net for information on how to reserve space to honor your senior in the 2019-2020 yearbook.

All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. Weâ€™re working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit theyâ€™ve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Boardâ€™s focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

shared_text:
The Red Ribbon Campaign
October 23, 2019 at 8:42 AM Â·

Do you know the history of the Red Ribbon Campaign? In response to the murder of DEA Agent Enrique Camarena, angered parents and youth in communities across the country began wearing Red Ribbons as a symbol of their commitment to raise awareness about the killing and the destruction caused by drugs in America. In 1988, the National Family Partnership sponsored the first National Red Ribbon Celebration. Today, the Red Ribbon serves as a catalyst to mobilize communities to educate youth and encourage participation in drug prevention activities. #RedRibbonWeek #KikiCamarena #sendamessgaestaydrugfree

Olney High School Robotics
October 9, 2019 at 6:25 PM Â·

Today was intense! Lots of work being done at the OHS Career Tech building this week.

Spirit Crew has been making spirit sticks and noise maker bottles. Recycle your bottles in the blue bucket at the HS!

Marketing Presentation crew has met each day at lunch discussing different business models.

Fab crew has assembled and mounted the robot arm. As well as completed programming for wheels and arm. The robot is mobile!

Notebook and Engineering Design crew have been busy from day 1 creating visual charts, making calculations, and maintaining documentation records.

Stay tuned for more about the teams Community Outreach efforts.

T minus 10 days until Demo Day (Oct 19).
